article.description:
Pau Gasol had 14 points and 11 rebounds,
and the Memphis Grizzlies beat the winless Golden State Warriors
96-67 Friday night.
article.headline: Pau's 14 points, 11 boards lift Memphis
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Poor shooting and ineffective rebounding made for a long night for the winless Golden State Warriors. Golden State made just 25 of 91 shots and didn't get many second chances in a 96-67 loss to the Memphis Grizzlies on Friday night. The Warriors' 27.5 shooting percentage was the lowest for a Grizzlies opponent. Now Golden State is 0-6 and off to its worst start since dropping nine straight to open the 1997-98 season. "I just think our confidence level is down right now," said guard Jason Richardson, who made just one of nine shots and scored five points in 27 minutes. "We have to stay focused because we can't give up. It's too early in the season to give up." Memphis (2-4) was led by Pau Gasol with 14 points and 11 rebounds. Stromile Swift grabbed 11 rebounds and Lorenzen Wright had 10 as the Grizzlies set a franchise record with 62, topping the 61 they had against the Los Angeles Clippers in 1998. The Warriors had 46 rebounds, getting 12 from Troy Murphy. Overall, the Grizzlies put on a faster-paced performance. "We had 17 blocks, and 13 of those were before the half," Memphis coach Hubie Brown said. "I thought everybody helped each other out tonight and got out on the break well. We were 12-18 off the break, and the blocked shots did a great job of setting those up." The Grizzlies have won two in a row since losing their first four games. Jason Williams scored 12 points and had five assists, and Mike Miller, Bonzi Wells and Wright each scored 10. The Warriors were led by Edwardo Najera who had 16 points on seven of nine shooting. Murphy had 15 points, and Mike Dunleavy had 10. "It's very disappointing," Dunleavy said of the poor start. "I thought we played pretty well in the preseason as far as togetherness. Mainly it's in a lack of offense, a lack of being able to make shots." The Grizzlies closed the second period with an 11-3 run to take a 51-32 lead at the half. Golden State shot just 23.4 percent from the field in the opening half, hitting on 11 of 47 attempts.

Game notes
Memphis F James Posey, with a strained left foot, was placed on the injured list. ... Golden State entered the game last in the NBA in points per game (82) and field gold percentage (.363). ... Brian Cardinal made his first appearance against the Warriors after leaving Golden State and signing with the Grizzlies as a free agent in July. He had four points in 17 minutes. Cardinal had the best season of his career with the Warriors last year, starting 11 times and averaging 9.6 points and 4.2 rebounds. ... Memphis was 3-1 against Golden State last season, but the Warriors hold an overall advantage of 21-15. ... Calling the evening "Military Appreciation Night," the Grizzlies hosted 1,200 service members from area bases. A military drill team performed at halftime.
